<h1>To Lord Dunmore</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">My Lord,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Williamsburg 2d Novembr 1773</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Urged to it by repeated applications from a number of officers whom I have had the honor to command in the service of this Colony, I take the liberty of addressing Your Excelly on the subject of the Lands which the Gentlemen conceive themselves entitled to under his Majestys bounty of October 1763.</p>
<p>The exception in favor of the Officers &amp; Soldiers, contained in his Majestys order in Council of the 6th of April last, they humbly conceive is so strong an implication of your Lordships right to grant them these Lands, as to remove every restraint you were under before;<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> and as there are no waste Lands to be had in this Colony, but such as lay upon the Western waters, they humbly pray for leave to survey on the river Ohio &amp; its waters below the mouth of Scioto (the western boundary of the New Colony, should it ever take place); apprehending that your Excellency hath an undoubted right to grant Patents for them, as these Lands have ever been considered as appertaining to Virginia
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-09-02-pb-0357">[357]</span>
warranted, as they have been informed, by the Colony-charter, &amp; sold by the Six Nations at the Treaty at Fort Stanwix in 1768: Nor is the right thereto, it is humbly presumed, by any means hurt by the nominal Line, commonly called the Ministerial Line, since that transaction seems to have been considered by Government as a temporary expedient (at the instigation of the Indian Agent) to satisfy the southern Indians, who as it is said, have disclaimed any right to the very Lands in contest; no other regard having been paid to it by the Ministers themselves.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>The Officers of Virginia Troops impressed with these sentiments, &amp; having undoubted reason to believe that there is no other chance left them to obtain their Lands, but on the Ohio, &amp; knowing at the same time that the officers of Pennsylvania under a belief that these Lands do appertain to Virginia, and that patents will be granted for them have surveyed 200,000 acres, would fain hope that they may be allowed to proceed by authority to make their surveys also, any where upon the ohio or its waters below the Scioto, humbly representing to your Lordship that a delay in this case, is, in effect, equal to a refusal, as the Country is spreading over with Emigrants, &amp; experience has convinced all those who have had occasion to attend to the matter, that these people when once fixed are not to be dispossessed, were it politic to attempt it.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0003-ptr">3</a></p>
<p>The officers have an entire confidence in your Lordships disposition to accelerate their just rightsthey have no other dependance&amp; hope to start equal with those other Officers, whose pretensions are not better founded than their own. The part I take in bringing this matter to a hearing will I hope meet with your Lordships excuse, as I am with the greatest respect My Lord Your Lordships Most Obt &amp; Most humble Servant</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0282-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>GW was referring to the Order in Council of 7 April barring the colonial governors from granting further lands in the West except to officers qualifying under the royal Proclamation of 1763 (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Acts of Privy Council, Colonial Series</span>, 5:36061).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>The Ministerial Line was the line drawn under the Proclamation of 1763.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-09-02-0282-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>The following paragraph appears in the council journals for 4 Nov.: His Excellency informed the Board that Col. Washing[ton] had applied on Behalf of the Officers and Soldiers intitled to Lands under his Majestys Proclamation
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-09-02-pb-0358">[358]</span>
issued in October 1763, they might be permitted to survey their several proportions on the Western Waters &amp; the Board advised his Excellency to issue his Warrants for that purpose (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ H. R. McIlwaine et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Executive Journals of the Council of Colonial Virginia&lt;/i&gt;. 6 vols. Richmond, 192566. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Exec. Journals of Virginia Council</span></span>, 6:549). The year before at a meeting in Fredericksburg in September 1772, GW and a number of other officers adopted resolutions to begin a campaign to secure land under the royal Proclamation of 1763, and in September 1773 GW approached Dunmore about land under the proclamation. See <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0073" class="document">Resolutions of Officers regarding the Royal Proclamation of 1763, 15 Sept. 1772</a>,<span class="choice deletion" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover_choice ] header=[]  body=[ Deleted: ' printed above,' &lt;span style='font-size: 90%'&gt;[[2014-11-24]]&lt;/span&gt; ]"><img alt="deletion" src="images/deletion_mark-trans.png" style="border:none;vertical-align: text-bottom; padding-right:2px"/></span> and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0246" class="document">GW to Lord Dunmore, 12 Sept. 1773</a>. See also <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-09-02-0188&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-09-02-0188-fn-0006#GEWN-02-09-02-0188-fn-0006" class="document">John Connolly to GW, 29 June 1773, n.6</a>.</p>

</div>
</div>
